    <title>Combined summary - Warning message when running wallet in Windows XP (or drop support?)</title>
    <updated>2023-06-08T19:51:53.616943+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-April/005254.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers had a discussion in 2014 regarding the security implications of using Windows XP and its compatibility with Bitcoin wallets. Microsoft had stopped providing security patches for the operating system, leaving it vulnerable to remote exploits that would not be fixed. Banks were warning customers against using XP for online banking, indicating that it was no longer secure enough for such activities. The question arose whether Bitcoin wallet software should drop support for XP completely, as it could compromise the security of the network.The email conversation between Wladimir, Pieter Wuille, and Kevin on April 16th, 2014, revolved around the topic of Windows XP's security. Pieter asked if they should assume that XP is not secure enough, to which Wladimir replied simply "Yes." He explained that as newer versions of Windows were released, people would begin analyzing patches to those versions in order to find vulnerabilities that could be exploited on XP. Therefore, XP would quickly become extremely insecure. Kevin then proposed adding an alert message to wallet installers to inform users that certain features may not run on XP.The Bitcoin Core team does not support Windows XP or any other distribution. They clarify that it doesn't make sense to support an OS platform that Microsoft no longer supports themselves. While it may not be their place to say whether XP is secure or not, if they support it, then it becomes a test and support issue, not a security issue. It's safe to run Bitcoin Core as a full node on XP, but people should be careful about using the wallet functionality as it is not supported.In a discussion on 04/16/2014 at 02:29 PM, Kevin suggested the idea of an autoupdate function for Bitcoin Core which pulls a work around off the server. However, this suggestion was quickly rejected with a strong statement that Bitcoin Core will never have an auto-update functionality. The reason behind this decision is that such a functionality would create a single point of failure which when compromised could result in the theft of every last bitcoin held in a Bitcoin Core wallet.The email thread also discussed warnings that Bitcoin Core should issue to users running on Windows XP and OS X 10.6. Pieter Wuille suggested that Bitcoin Core should detect when the user is running on Windows XP and warn them of the risks, while Mark Friedenbach argued that it's safe to run Bitcoin Core as a full node on XP and that only the wallet functionality should be approached with caution.Other discussions centered around multi-wallet support and added security measures like hardware security modules or multisig secured wallets. There were also debates about implementing an auto-update function for Bitcoin Core, with some developers rejecting this idea due to potential security risks.In conclusion, the discussion among Bitcoin developers emphasizes the importance of balancing innovation and progress with caution and evaluation of potential risks and benefits. While it may be safe to run Bitcoin Core nodes on Windows XP, wallet functionality on this system is not supported by the Bitcoin Core team and may compromise the security of keys. The options available include issuing a warning to users or redirecting them to a message on bitcoin.org about the dangers of using Windows XP. However, dropping XP support completely could lead to a loss of nodes on the network. Maintainers of other wallet software must also decide whether to drop XP support and from when.</summary>
